        <name>10.2.1 Find parabola, hence area between line and parabola</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p&gt;The diagram shows the graph of a parabola with turning point \(({@quad_TP[1]@},{@quad_TP[2]@})\), and the line with equation \(y={@k*x+linec@}\), both of which pass through the point \(({@B[1]@},{@B[2]@})\).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="margin-left:4em;margin-right:auto;"&gt;[[jsxgraph width='250px' height='250px']]
  JXG.Options.axis.ticks.majorHeight = 10;
  JXG.Options.axis.ticks.insertTicks = false;
  JXG.Options.axis.ticks.ticksDistance = 200;
  JXG.Options.text.fontSize = 16; 
  var board = JXG.JSXGraph.initBoard(divid, {boundingbox: {#BB#}, axis: true, showCopyright: false, showNavigation:false});
  var f = board.jc.snippet('{#quad#}', true, 'x', true);
  var plotf = board.create('functiongraph', [f,{#BB[1]#},{#BB[3]#}],{strokeColor:'#003399',strokeWidth:2});
  var g = board.jc.snippet('{#line#}', true, 'x', true);
  var plotg = board.create('functiongraph', [g,{#BB[1]#},{#BB[3]#}],{strokeColor:'#003399',strokeWidth:2});
  var pta = board.create('point',{#A#}, {name:'',size:2,fixed:true,strokeColor:'#003399',fillColor:'#003399', label: { offset: [0, {#-15*cy#}],anchorX: 'middle', anchorY: 'middle' }});
  var ptb = board.create('point',{#B#}, {name:'({#B[1]#},{#B[2]#})',size:2,fixed:true,strokeColor:'#003399',fillColor:'#003399', label: { offset: [-10, 0],anchorX: 'right', anchorY: 'middle' }});
  var ptc = board.create('point',{#quad_TP#}, {name:'({#quad_TP[1]#},{#quad_TP[2]#})',size:2,fixed:true,strokeColor:'#003399',fillColor:'#003399', label: { offset: [0, -5],anchorX: 'middle', anchorY: 'top' }});

 /* Creating a shaded area https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/jsxgraph/umlhu6CkGD0 */
 var area = board.create('curve', [[], []], {fillColor:'#003399',fillOpacity:0.15,strokeWidth:0});
 var upper = plotf;
 var lower = plotg;
 var limitL = {#ax#};
 var limitR = {#bx#};

 area.updateDataArray = function () {
 
/* code to get round the fact that we can't use the usual comparison operators due to HTML parsing - https://stackoverflow.com/a/49267601 */
 var precision=10;
 function isLessThan(a, b) {
   return Object.is((a-b)%1, -0);
 }
 function lte(a,b) {
   if(a==b) {
   	return true;
   } else {
   	return isLessThan(Math.floor(a*precision),Math.ceil(b*precision));
   }
 }
     var left = limitL, right = limitR, curve;
     var x = [left];
     var y = [upper.Y(left)];
     /* go through upper curve forwards, push all of its data points into the data array for area */
     curve = upper;    
     for (var i = 0; isLessThan(i, curve.numberPoints); i++) {
         if (lte(left,curve.points[i].usrCoords[1])) {
           if(lte(curve.points[i].usrCoords[1],right)) {
             x.push(curve.points[i].usrCoords[1]);
             y.push(curve.points[i].usrCoords[2]);
           }
         }
     }
     x.push(right);
     y.push(upper.Y(right));
 
     x.push(right);
     y.push(lower.Y(right));
     
     /* walk backwards through lower curve */
     curve = lower;
     for (var i = curve.numberPoints - 1; lte(0,i); i--) {
         if (lte(left,curve.points[i].usrCoords[1])) {
           if(lte(curve.points[i].usrCoords[1],right)) {
             x.push(curve.points[i].usrCoords[1]);
             y.push(curve.points[i].usrCoords[2]);
           }
         }
     }
 
     x.push(left);
     y.push(lower.Y(left));
     
     x.push(left);
     y.push(upper.Y(left));
     
     this.dataX = x;
     this.dataY = y;
 };
 
 board.update();

[[/jsxgraph]]&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;(a) &lt;/b&gt;What is the equation of the parabola?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; \(y=\)&amp;nbsp;[[input:ans1]][[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;(b) &lt;/b&gt;What is the value of \(k\)?&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; \(k=\)&amp;nbsp;[[input:ans2]][[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;(c) &lt;/b&gt;Calculate the shaded area, enclosed between the parabola and the line.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; The shaded area is&amp;nbsp;[[input:ans3]][[validation:ans3]][[feedback:prt3]]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;(a) &lt;/b&gt;From the turning point, the equation of the parabola must be of the form \(y={@(simp:false,'a*(x-quad_TP[1])^2+quad_TP[2])@}\).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Since it passes through&amp;nbsp;\(({@B[1]@},{@B[2]@})\), we have {@(simp:true,ev('a*(x-quad_TP[1])^2+quad_TP[2],x=B[1])=B[2])@}, thus {@'a=coeff(quad,x,2)@}.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;So the parabola has equation {@y=quad@}.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;(b) &lt;/b&gt;The line&amp;nbsp;\(y={@k*x+linec@}\) also passes through&amp;nbsp;\(({@B[1]@},{@B[2]@})\), so substituting gives {@(simp:false,ev(x*k+linec,x=B[1])=B[2])@}, from which we get \(k={@ta2@}\).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;(c) &lt;/b&gt;To find the shaded area, we need the points of intersection of the line and the parabola, so we solve: \[\begin{align*}{@quad@}&amp;amp;={@line@} \\ {@quad@}-({@line@}) &amp;amp;=0 \\ {@(simp:true,quad-line)@} &amp;amp;=0 \\ {@factor(quad-line)@}&amp;amp;=0, \end{align*}\] from which we see that the curves intersect when \(x={@ax@}\) or \(x={@bx@}\).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;So, the shaded area is given by \[\begin{align*} \int_{@ax@}^{@bx@} \left(\text{upper}-\text{lower}\right)\,dx &amp;amp;=&amp;nbsp;\int_{@ax@}^{@bx@} \left(({@line@})-({@quad@})\right)\,dx \\ &amp;amp;=&amp;nbsp;\int_{@ax@}^{@bx@} \left({@line-quad@}\right)\,dx. \\ &amp;amp;= \left[{@int1@}\right]_{@ax@}^{@bx@} \\ &amp;amp;=&amp;nbsp; \left({@(simp:false,make_multsgn("dot"),ev(int1,x=bx))@}\right)-\left({@ev(int1,x=ax)@}\right)&amp;nbsp;\\ &amp;amp;= {@ta3@}. \end{align*}\]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
